## Assessing the Association Between Endoscopic Tattooing and Lymph Node Yield in Rectal Cancer

Jordan Wlodarczyk, MD, MS, a,b Sean Dewberry, BS, c Dong Yoon, MD, b Christine Hsieh, MD, a Joongho Shin, MD, a Sang W. Lee, MD, a and Kyle G. Cologne, MD a, *

## abstract

Introduction: Preoperative endoscopic tattooing is an effective tool for intraoperative tumor localization in colon cancer. Endoscopic tattooing in rectal cancer may have unidentified benefits on lymph node yield, making it easier for pathologists to identify nodes during histopathologic assessment. There remains concern that tattoo ink may alter anatomical planes, increasing surgical difficulty.

Methods: Retrospective chart reviews from 2016 to 2021 of n ¼ 170 patients presenting with rectal cancer were divided into two groups: with ( n ¼ 79) and without ( n ¼ 91) endoscopic tattoos. Demographics, operative details, tumor characteristics, prior chemoradiation, and pathologic details were collected. Primary outcome was total lymph node yield. Secondary outcomes were rates of adequate ( > 12) nodes, margin status, and operative variables including operative time. Results: No differences between pathologic stage, tumor height, high inferior mesenteric artery ligation, operative times, conversion rate, or surgical approach (open versus minimally invasive) were noted between groups. Receipt of neoadjuvant chemoradiation was less frequent in the endoscopic tattooing group (53.2% versus 76.9%, P /C20 0.001). Total node number and rate of adequate lymph node yield were higher with endoscopic tattooing (20.5 /C6 7.6 versus 16.8 /C6 6.6 lymph nodes and 100.0% versus 83.5% adequate lymph node harvest, both P /C20 0.001). Rates of positive circumferential and distal margins and complete total mesorectal excision were also similar. Regression analysis identified endoscopic tattooing (Incidence Risk Ratio 1.17, 95% confidence interval 1.04-1.31) and operative time more than 300 min (Incidence Risk Ratio 0.88, 95% confidence interval 0.77-0.99) had significant effects on lymph node harvest. Removal of patients with inadequate lymph node yield resulted in similar rates of total and positive lymph nodes.

Conclusions: Endoscopic rectal tattooing is associated with increased lymph node yield (including after neoadjuvant chemoradiotherapy) without sacrificing oncologic or perioperative outcomes, although this effect is inconsistent when only considering patients with an adequate lymph node yield.

## Introduction

Endoscopic tattooing with dye has long been used to identify and localize tumors of the gastrointestinal tract (Fig.). India ink, methylene blue, and indocyanine green are the most commonly used agents in endoscopic tattooing. 1-3 With several studies reporting inadvertent excision of healthy bowel where the primary tumor was not adequately localized, the importance of endoscopic tattooing in colon cancer has been established as a significant tool in facilitating accurate and successful oncologic resection. 4-6

Alternative benefits of submucosal injection of dye have been suggested in the literature. After injection, dye travels to the lymph nodes where it is engulfed by macrophages and settles permanently. 7 This color change of the lymph nodes has the ability to augment the pathologic identification of lymph nodes to aid in adequate identification (and thereby staging). This could prove to be particularly useful after neoadjuvant chemoradiation, which disrupts the architecture of nodes and may make them more difficult to identify. 8,9 Previous studies assessing endoscopic tattooing's effect on lymph node yields after colon cancer resection have demonstrated mixed results. 10-13 Increasing lymph node yields demonstrate a survival benefit (perhaps because of more

![Image](data:image/png;base64,)

The potential for easier identification of nodes must be balanced against complications of endoscopic tattooing of lesions, which although rarely deserve some consideration. With inadvertent transmural injection and spillage rates as high as 14.3% in colon cancer, complications such as localized peritonitis, infected hematoma, abscess formation, inflammatory pseudotumor, and adhesions as a result of ink spillage have the potential to disrupt anatomical planes of dissection. 18 Limited anecdotal evidence resulting from these complications exists such as difficulty with plane identification in surgical dissection has led to low utilization of endoscopic tattooing in rectal cancer. 19 Furthermore, with low rectal lesions, tattoo is not required to identify the location of the lesion, which can be assessed by digital examination and endoscopy. This is markedly different than colonic lesions, where such landmarks do not exist and tattoo is critical for lesion localization.

Our study seeks to clarify some of these questions. We hypothesized that tattoo placement in rectal cancer will be associated with increased histopathologic lymph node yield/ identification without demonstration of deleterious effects on surrogates for operative difficulty or oncologic outcomes.

## Methods

This manuscript was prepared in accordance with the STROBE guidelines for retrospective cohort studies. 20

## Study design

Aretrospective review at a single tertiary academic institution from January 2016 to January 2021 of patients presenting with a diagnosis of rectal cancer was undertaken. Institutional review board approved waiver of consent and a prospective divisional database was queried. Patients were included in the study if their lesion was located within 15 cm of the anal verge or their medical records referred to the lesion as 'rectal' or below the third valve of Houston. Patients were excluded if their medical records did not contain an endoscopy report or if their oncologic operation did not encompass a total mesorectal excision (TME). Endoscopy reports from both the patients' referring endoscopist and their operating surgeon were reviewed for a written or photographic documentation of a tattoo. Choice of tattoo location and technique were done at the discretion of outside endoscopists. Because of the number of referring endoscopists performing the tattooing procedure and inconsistency in their documentation practices, tattoo variables were unable to be reliably assessed. A review of patient records abstracted demographic data, preoperative treatment course, receipt of neoadjuvant chemoradiotherapy, tumor characteristics, perioperative data (including operative time), and pathologic staging information. Pathologic staging information included data on quantity of lymph node harvest (including number of positive notes), distal and circumferential margin status, and presence of a complete TME ( versus incomplete specimen). The presence or absence of an

endoscopic tattoo on preoperative endoscopy report was used to stratify the rectal cancer patients into two cohorts.

## Pathologic evaluation

Specimens analyzed in this study had been obtained in patients undergoing surgical resection of rectal cancer and had been processed as per standard pathological procedures. To procure lymph nodes, prosectors manually harvested lymph nodes after dissecting the mesorectal fat. After gentle palpation of the fat and visual inspection, lymph nodes were identified and submitted for a histologic examination. The hematoxylin and eosin slides were reviewed to confirm the definitive diagnosis and pathological characteristics, including disease stage, tumor grade, and number of involved lymph nodes. Fat clearing techniques were not employed. If an inadequate number of lymph nodes were found in the oncologic sample, a senior pathologist re-evaluated the sample for additional lymph nodes. The tumor stage was assigned as per staging guidelines published by the American Joint Committee on Cancer in 2017. Stage was simplified by grouping stage 2 (2a and 2b), stage 3 (3a, 3b, and 3c), and stage four rectal cancers (4a, 4b, and 4c) into single groups. 21

## Primary outcomes

The primary outcome of the study was the total lymph node yield with oncologic resection.

## Secondary outcome

The secondary outcomes included rate of adequate lymph node harvest, as defined by the College of American Pathologists Consensus Statement in 1999 as /C21 12 lymph nodes, 22 rates of complete TME (intact mesorectum with only minor irregularities of a smooth mesorectal surface), 23 circumferential radial and distal margin positivity ( < 1mm), 24 surgical conversion rates from a minimally invasive approach to an open approach, and operative times. A subset analysis of patients previously undergoing neoadjuvant chemoradiation was undertaken to identify any additional benefit of endoscopic tattooing in this patient population. Patients with an inadequate lymph node yield were then excluded to eliminate bias from stage migration.

## Statistical analysis

All data were prepared and compiled using the Statistical Package for the Social Sciences program version 26.0 for Macintosh (SPSS Inc, Chicago, Illinois). Predictors of increased total lymph node harvest were analyzed with a negative binomial multivariate regression assessing predictors for an increased total lymph node yield. Any independent predictors of lymph node yield (with a P value < 0.2 on independent analysis) were included in multivariate analysis. Continuous variable distribution was assessed with the Kolmogorov e Smirnov test of normality. Variable distribution that differs significantly from a normal distribution was reported in medians and interquartile ranges while normally distributed data were reported with means and standard

deviations. Normally distributed continuous variables between the cohorts were compared by independent t -tests while non-normally distributed continuous variables were compared by Mann e Whitney U -tests. Nominal variables were compared with Fisher's exact tests.

## Results

## Participants

From January 2016 to January 2021, 212 patients were identified with a referring diagnosis of rectal cancer and who received an operation. Thirty five patients did not undergo a TME as part of their rectal cancer treatment and were excluded. Of the remaining 177 patients, seven were excluded because no endoscopy report was included in the medical records for review. Therefore, a total of 170 patients who underwent TME for rectal cancer treatment were included for study. No patients had a lateral lymph node dissection and all included TME surgery only.

During the study period, 79 patients (46.5%) underwent endoscopic tattooing of their lesion prior to surgery and 91 patients (53.5%) did not. The total cohort's average age was 61.0 /C6 12.6 y and they consisted of 58.2% males. The overall mean body mass index was 27.2 /C6 7.3 kg/m 2 and 59.4% of the cohort presented with an American Society of Anesthesiologists physical status classification system 25 score of two or higher. A large portion (65.9%) of the total cohort received neoadjuvant chemoradiation prior to their operation. Patients presented with a pathologic stage as follows: complete response (pCR) 17.1%, Stage one disease 20.0%, Stage two disease 27.1%, Stage three disease 27.6%, and Stage four disease 5.3%. Average distance of the tumor from the anal verge was 8.7 /C6 3.4 cm. An operative procedure performed for TME was a low anterior resection in 96.5% of cases and the operative approach consisted of a laparoscopic approach in 55.9%, robotic-assisted approach in 28.8%, and open approach in 15.3%. The conversion rate from minimally invasive surgery to open technique was 6.5%. The average operative time was 282.6 /C6 112.6 min. The average number of positive lymph nodes obtained in the specimen was 0.91 /C6 2.2 and mean total lymph nodes was 18.5 /C6 7.3. The average rate of adequate lymph node dissection ( /C21 12 nodes identified) was 91.2%. Complete TME was achieved in 78.8 % of cases reporting quality of TME resection. Negative circumferential margins were found in 94.1%. Distal margins were negative 98.2% of the time.

## Endoscopic tattooing cohort descriptive data and outcomes

The tattoo group and the no-tattoo group had statistically similar descriptive variables except for the administration of neoadjuvant chemoradiation (tattoo: 53.2% versus no-tattoo: 76.9%, P /C20 0.001). Pathologic stage, distance to the anal verge, and average operative time were similar (all P > 0.05) (Table 1).

When surgical oncologic outcomes were considered, there was no difference in negative distal and circumferential margins and rates of complete TME (all P > 0.05). Patients with

an endoscopic tattoo had higher numbers of positive lymph nodes found on pathologic evaluation (1.32 /C6 2.92 versus 0.55 /C6 1.24, P ¼ 0.032) and average total lymph nodes found on pathologic evaluation (20.5 /C6 7.6 versus 16.8 /C6 6.6 lymph nodes, P < 0.001). The rate of adequate lymph node dissection was also higher in patients with an endoscopic tattoo (100.0% versus 83.5%, P < 0.001) (Table 1). After excluding patients with an inadequate lymph node yield (all of which were in the notattoo group), significant differences remained between groups with respect to receipt of neoadjuvant chemoradiation (53.2% versus 76.3%). In addition, tumor distance to the anal verge was higher in the tattoo group (9.3 /C6 3.4 versus 8.2 /C6 3.5). The previously noted difference between total lymph node yield and total positive lymph nodes disappeared (Table 2).

A subgroup analysis was performed on patients who received neoadjuvant chemoradiation. The tattoo group and the no-tattoo group had similar demographic variables. When surgical oncologic outcomes were compared, endoscopic tattoo and no-endoscopic tattoo groups only differed by a statistically higher total lymph node yield (20.6 /C6 5.7 versus 16.2 /C6 6.5, P < 0.001) and rate of adequate lymph node dissection (100% versus 82.9%, P ¼ 0.003) in the endoscopic tattoo group (Table 3).

## Predictive factors of increased total lymph node yield with oncologic resection

Nine variables were independent predictors of total lymph node yield and were included in a multivariate analysis

(Table 4). Only the presence of an endoscopically placed tattoo and an operative time more than 300 min had significant effects on the total lymph node yield on multivariate analysis. The placement of an endoscopic tattoo produced an incidence risk ratio of 1.17 (95% confidence interval [CI] 1.04-1.31) and increased the total lymph node yield (marginal mean 20.25 versus 18.26 lymph nodes). Operative time more than 300 min produced an incidence risk ratio of 0.87 (95% CI 0.76-0.98), suggesting that with increasing length of operation resulted in the decreased total lymph node yield (marginal mean 17.90 versus 20.66 lymph nodes). Receipt of neoadjuvant chemoradiation, high inferior mesenteric artery ligation, complete TME, pathologic stage, operation performed, and surgical platform used had no significant effect on the total lymph node harvest (Table 4). When considering patients only with an adequate lymph node yield, this regression was done again (Table 5). In this group, operative time > 300 min remained a predictor; however, tattoo placement was no longer statistically significant (odds ratio 1.08, 95% CI 0.97-1.20).

## Discussion

Our study confirms our hypothesis that endoscopic tattooing is associated with improved lymph node yield, particularly in the setting of neoadjuvant chemoradiotherapy. We believe this is most likely due to improved identification of nodes by tattoo deposits visualized within the node structures. We also

Two other small studies also suggest lymph node yield increases with endoscopic tattooing, similar to our study. 17,26 One found that placement of a tattoo was associated with a 19.2% higher rate of adequate lymph node harvest (odds ratio 95% CI 1.171-9.151). 17 Another study 26 demonstrated a 51% increase in the total lymph nodes found on pathologic evaluation (mean 13.3 with tattoo versus 8.8 without) along with an increased propensity to locate smaller lymph nodes (1-3 mm lymph nodes 5.9 with tattoo versus 3.1 without). This aforementioned study demonstrated that 38% of patients with an endoscopically placed tattoo had ink uptake in their retrieved lymph nodes facilitating easy identification of lymph nodes. This suggests that increases in lymph node yields could be attributable to easier identification of smaller lymph nodes by pathologists after endoscopic tattooing.

In our study, the placement of an endoscopic tattoo was associated with an absolute increase in the total lymph node yield by 3.7 lymph nodes (22.0% absolute increase). In addition, an increase in the rate of adequate lymph node harvest of 16.5% was noted in patients receiving an endoscopic tattoo. An important potential confounding factor is the receipt of neoadjuvant chemoradiotherapy. We therefore evaluated only our neoadjuvant chemoradiation cohort to isolate a potentially confounding variable. We found that this group had an even higher total lymph node yield (by 4.4 nodes or 27.2%) and a 17.1% increased rate of adequate lymph node dissection (to 100%), again suggesting that tattoo may aid

visualization of these nodes. When we remove patients with an inadequate lymph node yield (all of whom interestingly were in the no-tattoo group), some of the previous findings disappear. However, this restriction also introduced new differences between groups, so it is difficult to know how to interpret these findings.

Overall, reported rates of adequate lymph node harvest and total number of lymph nodes harvested were lower than that seen in our study (39.5% versus our 91.2% adequate lymph node harvest and 20.6 /C6 5.7 versus 13.3 /C6 7.4 our total lymph nodes harvested). 27-29 There likely are institutional, technique and pathologist-level differences that make comparison difficult. Our academic center uses residents who do a portion of the initial gross evaluation, which is then reviewed by a senior or attending pathologist. When inadequate harvest is identified, a second pass is performed. It does seem safe to say that tattoo does appear to be associated with increased lymph node identification. The impact this may have on stage migration because of increased node identification is an interesting one but the present study is not sufficient to provide an answer.

Our study was limited by our overall small sample size and lack of extended follow-up, which limits our ability to report survival and recurrence in our patients. Due to insurance limitations and most of our patients returning to their referring oncologist/endoscopist after surgical excision of their cancer, our follow-up data are incomplete. We are unable to accurately report survival outcomes. There is also a selection bias and lack of a standardized protocol for what patient and

Our pathologists and their ancillary staff analyze approximately 50-70 low anterior resection cases per year and experience likely plays a large role in the ability to isolate lymph nodes that have been affected by radiation and chemotherapy. This may limit the generalizability of our study. With continued time and communication with outside referring oncologists we can gain the opportunity to assess for endoscopic tattooing's effect on overall survival. We also did not observe in our

regression analysis the association of neoadjuvant chemoradiation with decreased lymph node yields which has been observed in other studies. 9 This could have been in part due to low power of our study. Finally, due to the retrospective nature of study and documentation limitations it becomes difficult to assess what effect surgeon volume and experience has on the decision to perform an extended lymphadenectomy. It is possible that more experienced surgeons based on their intraoperative assessment of stained lymph nodes within vascular pedicles may change their surgical plans.

IMA ¼ Inferior Mesenteric Artery; TME ¼ Total Mesorectal Excision; LAR ¼ Low anterior resection; APR ¼ abdominoperineal resection.

In total, our retrospective cohort study demonstrated a positive association between endoscopic tattooing of rectal cancer and an increased total lymph node yield. Unique to the literature, this study finds no difference in surrogate measures chosen for surgical difficulty between tattooed and nontattooed lesions, although further study is required to confirm this.

## Conclusions

Endoscopic rectal tattooing appears to be associated with increased lymph node yield without sacrificing oncologic or perioperative outcomes. This observation persists when considering only patients who received neoadjuvant therapy but disappears when excluding those with an inadequate lymph node yield (who were only seen in the no-tattoo group). Further study is needed to assess the effect of tattooing on stage migration, although it may be a useful tool to aid node identification.
